observations.managementAction:
a. The Inventory Management:
1. Reconstitute or reactivate the Inventory Committee through the issuance of an Executive Order. Subsequently, direct them to prepare the PIP for approval of the Chief Executive and submit the same to the Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
2. Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all PPE following the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team;
3. Direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO - Designate to reconcile their respective PPE records;
4. Direct the Municipal Accountant to exhaust all efforts to fully identify the PPE with lump sum balances and at the same time secure the documents to reconcile them with the Inventory Report of the GSO;
5. Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE;
6. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to reclassify to Seaport Systems account payment for the land expansion and port development of Mobo amounting to ₱2,996,269.52 erroneously recorded as Land and Other Structures accounts, respectively; and
7. Require the GSO - Designate and the Municipal Accounting Office to avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecogntion of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances.

observations.recommendation:
We recommend and reiterated the following to Management:

Require the Inventory Committee to immediately submit the RPCPPE and RPCLRN for CY 2022, ensure the conduct of annual inventory-taking of all PPE and timely submit the RPCPPE for all PPE together with the RPCLRN of the LGU within the prescribed period;

Instruct the GSO-Designate to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards and the Municipal Accountant of the Property Ledger Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to immediately transfer the completed PPE recorded in the TF to the GF and to effect the necessary adjusting entries for the prior years’ depreciation expense;

Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and

Assess its existing organizational structure and consider the appointment of a permanent GSO to perform the duly designated duties and responsibilities effectively and efficiently.

We recommended that Management:

Immediately submit the contracts with corresponding supporting documents for infrastructure projects amounting to ₱39,273,165.71 as well as the lacking supporting documents on the related payments. Henceforth, all perfected contracts together with its supporting documents must be submitted for review and evaluation to the Office of the Auditor within five working days from execution of contract;

Submit plausible explanation/justification on the deficiencies and discrepancies noted in the submitted documents;

Strictly adhere to the above cited provisions on the posting of performance security, warranty security and release of retention money to the contractor; and

Direct concerned officials to ensure that payments on procurements for infrastructure projects are properly supported with complete documentation.

We recommended that Management:

Observe judicious management of DRRM funds, to include planning and budgeting of the total available funds from the GF and Special TF, and optimal utilization through the timely and full implementation of LDRRM related PPAs; 

Explain the improper use of MOOE funds for Capital Outlay expenditures and refrain from utilizing the fund without an available appropriation, otherwise, ensure to make the necessary adjustments in the plan and budget, if necessary;

Stop using the fund for administrative purposes or non-allowable PPAs and exclusively utilize the same in accordance with the MDRRMFIP for projects or purposes which will be more effective in strengthening the disaster preparedness and response capabilities of the LGU and its community; and

Propose for the inclusion of MOOE items in the annual appropriation for the administrative expenses and operation of the MDRRM Office.

We recommended the following:

The Officer in Charge of the Waterworks System must furnish the Municipal Accountant of the Monthly Billing, Reading, and Payment Monitoring Report for basis of the latter in recording the actual income earned and its corresponding receivable;

The Municipal Accountant, on periodic basis, must recognize the Impairment Loss – Loans and Receivables at an appropriate rate on the closed accounts/water service disconnection of consumers having unpaid water bills pursuant to IPSAS guidance that receivables must be presented at net realizable value during the reporting date;

Management must strictly enforce the disconnection policy as basis for impartial water service disconnection to consumers who were unable to pay the water bills after due date. Further, aforesaid policy must be incorporated in the Service Application for Water Connection duly signed by the applicant and notarized by a notarial officer;

As a matter of internal control, personnel from the Accounting Office by way of an Office Order issued by the Municipal Mayor, be assigned to randomly check the meter reading submitted to that office against the actual reading of consumers’ water meters.  Discrepancy noted or abnormal readings must be reported and investigated, copy furnish the Audit Team.

We recommended that:

The LGU, through the BAC, MPDO and Municipal Engineer, to effectively plan and implement immediately all developmental projects within the calendar year in order that stakeholders may not be deprived from the benefits and enjoyment of government projects.  All planned developmental projects must be aligned with the provincial, regional, and national developmental projects for efficiency, effectiveness, and economy of its implementation;

The BAC must strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 9184, its Revised IRR and other applicable laws and regulations in the evaluation of the bidders;

The LGU must submit Appraisal Report on the purchase of dump truck to establish the reasonable acquisition cost of the unit based on the actual conditions of the reconditioned truck.  Also, the supplier must submit LTO Accreditation Permit as Dealer/Seller of motor vehicle as required by laws and regulation on the matter; and

If the infrastructure work is satisfactorily done and on schedule, stop the practice of retaining 10 per cent from progress billing after 50 per cent completion, instead, require contractors to post Warranty Security for all completed and accepted projects. The Warranty Security is also applied to the delivery and acceptance of the reconditioned Dump Truck for a period of one year.

We recommended that the LSB:

Obtain/secure the required DepEd approved SIP, DEDP and other information from the DepEd RO on the allocation of each school from the National Budget as contained in the NEP, which supposedly were the basis for the preparation and approval by the LSB of the SEF Budget and furnish the Audit Team, for reference and review purposes. Henceforth, the LSB must strictly follow the mandated required processes and documents in planning and budgeting for SEF under the revised guidelines on the use of SEF; 

Incorporate in the budget programs and activities intended for ECCD as required under Section 7 (b) of RA No. 10410 and satisfactory explanation is requested why ECCD was not given allocation despite the sufficient revenue generated under 1 per cent SET; and

We recommended that the LCE:

Enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding CAs, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strengthen the internal control on the grant and liquidation of cash advances by complying with the provisions under Sections 4 and 5 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and bearing in mind the criminal liability provided by law;

Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within the prescribed period;

Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances; and 

Verify the collectability of unliquidated cash advances of more than 10 years, otherwise, request for authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management:

Enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding cash advances, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strengthen the internal control on the grant and liquidation of cash advances by complying with the provisions under Section Nos. 4 and 5 of the COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within the reglementary period; 

Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances; and

Verify the collectability of unliquidated cash advances of more than 10 years, otherwise, request the authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the LGU officials and employees to submit promptly their claims together with complete relevant supporting documents to the Office of the Municipal Accountant;

Hire additional competent personnel in the Accounting Office to facilitate the voluminous transactions occurring each month in the Municipality, and to hasten the process of submission of the necessary accounts to the Office of the Auditor;

Evaluate the process of preparing the disbursement vouchers, RCIs, RCDs, RAAFs, and relevant documents to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years and be reminded that processing of vouchers must only be undertaken when they were properly approved and with complete documentation; and

Remind the concerned officials and employees of the administrative or criminal liability, under Section 39 (1) (3) of PD No. 1445 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code, as amended by Section 41 of RA No. 10951, which may be imposed as a consequence of their inability or refusal to render accounts without justifiable cause.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Supply Officer to conduct pre-repair evaluation/inspection and post-repair evaluation/inspection of all its government vehicles subjected to repairs;

Require that the Report of Waste Material be prepared by the Supply Officer and approved by the Local Chief Executive;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a ledger card for the expenses incurred regarding repair and maintenance of every vehicle owned by the Agency to monitor whether the property is economically repairable; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to always ensure that future payments are properly taken up and recorded in the books in its appropriate accounts.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require that an actual inventory-taking of all assets or PPEs of the LGU be conducted each year pursuant to Section 124, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGUs; that the relevant RPCPPE be submitted not later than January 31 of each year to the Office of the Auditor; and that the same be reconciled with the records of the Municipal Accountant; 

Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and PPELC, respectively, for all the Agency’s PPEs;

Consider creating a GSO who will discharge on a full-time basis the procurement and issuance of supplies and property, maintain updated Property Cards per category on all Agency’s assets as recorded in the list of PPEs of accounting records, and facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCPPE;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the collecting officers, by issuing a demand letter, to remit the unremitted collections amounting in total to ₱1.16 million and to turn-over all future collections intact to the Municipal Treasurer and not to retain portion of them pursuant to Sections 8 and 26 of COA Circular No. 92-382;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to closely supervise the collecting officers and monitor their daily collections and remittances and require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary ledgers for each of the collecting officers;

Strengthen internal control over collections and remittances to avoid retention of big amounts of money in the hands of the collecting officers and consider the promulgation and implementation of a policy on the following:

On the turnover of daily collections, such as establishing a cut-off on the time of turnover which will give the Municipal Treasurer enough time to deposit the turned-over collections; and

On imposing a penalty for holding of collections for several days in the hands of collecting officers.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Make representations with the DBP for reconciliation of their records and obtain copies of debit memos and other related loan documents as reference in adjusting the books to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;

Strengthen accounting controls over loans payable by reviewing thoroughly the amortization schedule given by the bank and carefully analyzing transaction before recording in the books and updating entries of both records;

We recommended and reiterated the following:

Require all Aos/Officials and employees to settle their respective cash advances at the end of the year to reflect the correct balances of the accounts affected in the books of accounts of the Agency;

Henceforth, avoid granting subsequent cash advances to Aos with outstanding cash advances and withhold the salaries and/or any amount due those Aos who were unable to comply with the pertinent rules and regulations on cash advances in accordance with the afore-cited law and regulations;

Cause for the immediate liquidation of the outstanding cash advances amounting to ₱3,673,247.77 as of December 31, 2022 and submit the liquidation report or proof of refund/s, if there are any, to the Auditor for post-audit;

Send Demand Letters to the concerned Aos, with unliquidated cash advances for monitoring purposes;

Adhere strictly to the guidelines in the granting, utilization and settlement of cash advances as enunciated in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and

Immediate submission to the Audit Team of liquidations with its complete supporting documents for travel related cash advances for CYs 2022 and 2021 amounting to ₱2,957,186.33 and ₱795,808.24, respectively, which were liquidated and recorded under the Travelling Expenses-Local account. Henceforth, promptly submit settlement of cash advances for travel together with the monthly accounts.

We reiterated that Management complies with the following audit recommendations:

To strictly adhere to the prior years’ audit recommendation for the creation of the Inventory Committee, who will be tasked to conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE accounts, prepare and submit the corresponding reconciled RPCPPE including the prescribed Report of Inventory on Unserviceable Property to the Office of the Auditor on or before January 31 of each year;

Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and install corrective measures thereof, such as revisiting Agency’s assets if bearing property stickers and property numbers that would serve as controls for its accountability;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Inventory Committee documents pertaining to the details of PPE accounts such as infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures including the on-going constructions to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records;

Require the MGSO complete maintenance of AREs for proper identification of persons responsible/accountable thereof and be indicated in the Inventory Report/Listings of Agency’s properties; and

Direct the MGSO and Municipal Accountant to maintain the respective complete property records, such as PCs and PPELC for PPE as well as records on land, buildings and infrastructure assets of the Agency, trace out prior years’ accounts and reconcile their respective records; and

The MGSO as the front liner of LGU in property management, must be recommended for appropriate training relative thereto in order to cope with the required deliverables (such as the reporting and recording processes of the LGU properties) and to strictly adhere to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties. In addition, all available property records from the former Property Officer must be turned over to the incumbent MGSO for her reference and record.

We recommended that Management:
Require the driver to properly fill-out the Driver’s Trip Ticket prior to travel and require all authorized passengers to affix their signature/s on the trip tickets. Otherwise, refrain from allowing the government vehicle to be used for travel in the absence of the same; 

Prepare and submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Fuel Consumption at the end of each month to the Auditor, for verification; 

Require concerned official to submit the required lacking supporting documents; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents as well as reconcile the differences noted in the recording of monthly transactions and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977.

We recommended that Management:

Enjoin the MDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;

Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;

Direct the MDRRMO to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded, including the list of PPAs to be undertaken out of the unexpended balances under the STF using the prescribed format in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2012-002; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to ensure in the succeeding years that the transfer of actual cash pertaining to the unexpended balances of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE to the STF be made immediately at year-end pursuant to the provisions of RA No. 10121 and COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned officials to submit the required lacking disbursement voucher and the required supporting documents in accordance with Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001;

We recommended that Management:
Reconstitute or reactivate the Inventory Committee through the issuance of an Executive Order. Subsequently, direct them to prepare the PIP for approval of the Chief Executive and submit the same to the Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all PPE following the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO - Designate to reconcile their respective PPE records;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to exhaust all efforts to fully identify the PPE with lump sum balances and at the same time secure the documents to reconcile them with the Inventory Report of the GSO;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to reclassify to Seaport Systems account payment for the land expansion and port development of Mobo amounting to ₱2,996,269.52 erroneously recorded as Land and Other Structures accounts, respectively; and
Require the GSO - Designate and the Municipal Accounting Office to avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecogntion of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances.

We recommended that Management:
Enjoin the MDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Advise the Municipal Budget Officer to ascertain that all charges in the LDRRMF are related to four thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management and strictly adhere to the provisions of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC Nos. 2013-1 and 2014-1;
Create a special trust fund bank account for the unexpended DRRMF and upon creation, immediately draw a check from the GF to transfer the unexpended current and prior years’ LDRRMF balances to the TF books under Trust-Liability DRRM account. Likewise, ensure that the unexpended balance of QRF and DRRMF-MOOE for each year be timely transferred at year-end with the corresponding cash back-up in order to reflect the correct balances of the cash and liability accounts in the FS;
Require the MDRRMO to include under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years in the preparation of LDRRMF Investment Plan; and
Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer and MDRRMO to conduct annual reconciliation of their respective records on the utilization of LDRRMF to avoid inconsistent balances on their reports and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted thereon accordingly.

We recommended that Management:
Immediately submit the lacking DV and required complete supporting documents for the subject CAs in a sealed envelope and with a covering transmittal letter enumerating the submissions as required under Section 6.3.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND JC No. 2015-001;
Require the LCE to immediately liquidate the CAs and submit the required documents to the Confidential and Intelligence Fund Audit Unit of COA, copy furnished the Audit Team of the duly received transmittal letter;
Limit CA granted for CF to the requirement of three months and the total amount for CF shall not exceed 30 percent of the total annual amount allocated for the LGU’s POP; and
Submit explanation for the delayed submission of CA voucher, Liquidation Reports and other noted deficiencies.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC to stop the practice of splitting of contracts and strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 9184 in all procurements;
Render an explanation or justification on the resort to alternative method of procurement;
Submit the lacking supporting documents for each transaction; and
Stop the practice of indicating brand names in the PR and adhere to the provision of RA No. 9184 to avoid disallowance in audit.

We recommended that Management:
Strictly adhere to the above cited provisions on the procurement of infrastructure projects. Henceforth, all perfected contracts together with its supporting documents must be submitted for auditorial and technical review and evaluation to the Office of the Auditor within five working days from execution of contract;
Direct concerned officials to submit explanation on the deficiencies noted and required lacking documents forming part of the contract; and
Direct BAC Chairman to maintain a checklist of required documents to be submitted and ensure that procurement of infrastructure projects is properly supported with complete documentation;

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned officials to submit lacking DVs and the required lacking supporting documents in accordance with Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001, otherwise, the subject disbursements will be disallowed in audit;
Require the Municipal Accountant to impose ten percent withholding on every progress payment made to the contractor as retention money in accordance with Section 6.1, Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
Submit explanation for the non-submission of DVs for progress payments and other noted deficiencies; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001.

We recommended that Management:
Follow up on the approval of the 10-year Municipal SWM Plan to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 19 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes;
Provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and
Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct the actual physical count of all PPE in accordance with the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, COA Circular No. 2015-008 and COA Circular No. 2020-006 to properly prepare and submit the prescribed RPCPPE and RPCLRN within the prescribed period;
Instruct the GSO-Designate, to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map, updated Property Cards, Local Road Network Property Cards and PAR;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
i. 	Prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, LRNLC, including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the General Ledger (GL) account balances and with the property records;
ii.	Adjust the items erroneously recorded as PPE to the appropriate accounts;
Prepare a detailed lapsing schedule in computing the yearly depreciation expense and adjust the books for depreciation expenses erroneously computed and recognized in the previous years; and
Require the GSO-Designate and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and reiterated that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Cause the creation of a task force to establish a set of policies and procedures with reference to existing COA policies and procedures on cash management system to address the above cited weaknesses in internal control and stop the illegal and irregular practices such as lapping of collections and grant of vales and borrowings by officials and employees from the cash on hand;
Require the OIC-MT and Municipal Accountant to conduct a complete reconciliation between the OIC-MT and Accounting records to come up with the accurate undeposited collection of the OIC-MT and cause the temporary relief of the OIC-MT from collection and disbursing functions while the reconciliation is ongoing and the collections remained not deposited;
Direct the OIC-MT to immediately deposit the balance of his undeposited collections under all funds;
Require the Liquidating Officer and all the Collecting Officers to remit/deposit their collections intact and in full amount, daily, weekly or as soon as the amount of collection reaches ₱5,000.00;
Require the Liquidating Officer to properly check the remittances together with the duplicate and unissued/unused AFs and require the remittance of previously issued AFs before new AFs are issued;
Impose administrative sanctions or institute disciplinary actions to erring AOs, if warranted.

We reiterated and recommended that Management:
Demand immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding CA, especially from the OIC-MT and all AOs and employees still connected with the LGU, pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;
Cause the temporary relief of the OIC-MT from performing disbursing functions considering the substantial amount of his unliquidated CA and undeposited collections;
Require the OIC-MT and Municipal Accountant to submit the unsubmitted Check DVs and Cash DVs/Liquidations of the OIC-MT totaling ₱137,636,332.21;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the unsubmitted Check DVs and Liquidations Reports of officers and employees totaling ₱ 1,815,535.00;
Be reminded that an official/employee who is separated from the service caused by reassignment/transfer/retirement/death, must not be given clearance unless their outstanding CA are first settled;
Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the grant, utilization and liquidation of CA and avoid granting additional CA unless the previous CA is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made pursuant to Section 89 of PD No. 1445;
Institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring AOs/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of CA, if warranted; and
File a request to the Commission on Audit for authority to write-off and/or adjust the dormant or non-moving accounts as prescribed in COA Circular Nos. 2016-005. The request must be duly supported by the documents required in the said Circular.

We recommended that Management require:
The GSO-Designate and other concerned Heads of Offices to immediately submit to the Accounting Office, copy furnished the Audit Team, the documents supporting the issuance, consumption or distribution of various inventories held for consumption and distribution;
The Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchase of inventories in the appropriate inventory accounts and the issuance, consumption and distribution thereof as expense upon receipt of RIS and SSMI of a given period and supported with a duly accomplished and fully accounted distribution list and proof of actual distribution together with other required documents;
The Inventory Committee to conduct the required physical count of all supplies and materials and submit the RPCI; and
The Accounting Office and the Property Office to maintain complete and updated Stock Ledger Cards and Stock Cards, respectively.

We recommended that Management require the concerned Officials to:
Submit the subject CY 2023 contracts, lacking DVs with their supporting documents and explain for the noted deficiencies in the submitted documents;
Ensure that the validity period of the performance security posted by the contractors is in accordance with Section 62.2.2 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
Require the posting of warranty security as one of the documentary requirements for final payment and ensure that the validity period is in accordance with Section 62.2.3 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
Exercise strictest scrutiny in the preparation of bidding documents and conduct of procurement activities, especially the bid evaluation, in accordance with the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and other relevant procurement guidelines; and
Ensure that the contracts and payments are duly supported with complete documentary requirements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001, COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 and COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that Management require the concerned officials to:
Submit the lacking documentary requirements on the subject procurement transactions and explain for the deficiencies noted therein;
Conduct judicious and meticulous procurement planning and proper determination of the mode of procurement to be used which must be indicated in the PPMPs of each Offices to be consolidated in the APP;
Strictly abide with the procedural guidelines for the appropriate alternative mode of procurement;
Ensure that all procurements must be made from technically, legally and financially capable suppliers of goods and services; and
Ensure completeness of documentary requirements for the respective alternative mode of procurement and specific documents required for the procurement of drugs and medicines.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the LDRRMO to submit the LDRRMFIP showing the allocation of LDRRMF for both current and the unexpended balance of the prior years’ DRRMF;
Cause the timely and full implementation of all programmed DRRMF PPAs;
Ensure that the cash transfer of the unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE must be made at the end of the year in accordance with Item 5.1.10 of COA Circular No. 2021-002;
Revert to the GF the unspent balances under the STF account of DRRMF for CY 2017 and prior years; and
Refrain from charging against the LDRRMF those expenditures not pertaining to disaster risk reduction and management or not in accordance with the primary purpose for which the fund was established, otherwise, these transactions shall be disallowed in audit.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct the Municipal Accountant, OIC-MT and MBO to immediately submit the subject accounts, reports and books of accounts, otherwise, the subject transactions will be suspended in audit;
Require the OIC-MT to submit on time the paid DVs, Payrolls and issued AFs with the accompanying financial reports to the Accounting Office;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
i. Ensure the completeness of the supporting documents and the approval and signature of the concerned officials and employees for every transaction before processing the DVs;
ii. Submit these accounts and reports within ten days after receipt to the Office of the Auditor for verification and post-audit;
iii. Timely record the transactions in the books of accounts, prepare a monthly trial balance and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor on or before the 20th day of the ensuing month;
iv. Ensure the submission of the complete year-end FS, general and SLs and supporting schedules on or before the 14th day of February of the succeeding year;
Direct the MBO to prepare a monthly SAAOB, reconcile with the accounting records and timely submit the same to the Office of the Auditor, through the Accounting Office.
If warranted, institute suspension of payment of their salaries until they have complied with the aforesaid requirements pursuant to Section 122 (2) of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert effort in reconciling and establishing the unremitted trust collections from prior years’ transactions and once established, accordingly remit the same to the respective government agencies;
Prepare and maintain SLs on the composition of the balances of Due to BIR for withheld taxes on compensation and government money payments, and Dues to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth for premiums, contributions and loan amortization, and other subsidiary accounts, as needed;
Appropriately charge and collect from the suppliers/contractors/employees to whom the overremittance of withheld taxes, premiums or contributions pertain; and
Henceforth, ensure the conduct of monthly reconciliation of remittances against withheld/recognized amounts to prevent recurrence of unreconciled or inaccurate remittance of balances.

We recommended that Management direct the concerned Officials to:
Explain for the delays incurred in the implementation of the project;
Submit the approved suspension and resume work orders and other relevant documents pertaining to the delays and the proposed extension of contract time, if any;
Strengthen its monitoring and supervision of the overall project implementation and formulate measures to address the causes of delay; and
Direct the Contractor to exert best efforts to timely implement and complete the PRDP Subproject.

We recommended that Management:
Require the officials and employees to submit liquidation reports/settle their outstanding CAs, otherwise impose appropriate legal actions to enforce its settlement;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to officials and employees without first liquidating the previous CA;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to limit the CA of Assistance to Individuals under Crisis Situation (AICS) to one month expenditure only so as to avoid accumulation of huge CA balances and difficulty in liquidation;
File a request for authority to write off dormant CAs as well as the CAs of deceased Accountable Officers (AOs), in accordance with the guidelines provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005; and
Strictly adhere to the above-mentioned laws, rules and regulations relative to granting and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
